      <app id="app1">
        <title>APPENDIX A: DERIVATION OF THE NONCENTRALITY PARAMETERS</title>
        <p>We derive noncentrality parameters for the three testing scenarios outlined in the main text: the trend test, the deviation test, and the interaction test. In each case, we consider a Wald test using a logistic regression model. While a score test is standard in the first scenario, deriving the noncentrality parameter for such a test gives the same result (derivation not shown), and the two tests are nonetheless asymptotically equivalent [Cox and Hinkley, <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="b7">1974</xref>].</p>
        <p>Let the number of cases and controls be <italic>S</italic> and <italic>R</italic>, respectively, the total number of individuals in the sample be <italic>N</italic>, and the proportion of cases in the sample be &#x3C6; = <italic>S</italic>/<italic>N</italic>. At a given SNP, let the number of individuals with genotypes 0, 1, and 2 be <italic>n</italic><sub>0</sub>, <italic>n</italic><sub>1</sub>, and <italic>n</italic><sub>2</sub>, respectively. Let the subscript <italic>i</italic> refer to individual <italic>i</italic>.</p>
        <sec>
