          <p>
            <disp-formula id="m41">
              <graphic xlink:href="gepi0035-0278-m41"/>
              <label>(A.2)</label>
            </disp-formula>
          </p>
          <p>Note that the terms containing (1&#x2212;2&#x3C6;) disappear when &#x3C6; = 1/2 (equal number of cases and controls), meaning that these approximations are particularly good in that case&#x2014;e.g. <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="gepi0035-0278-mu25.jpg" mimetype="image"/></inline-formula> becomes <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="gepi0035-0278-mu26.jpg" mimetype="image"/></inline-formula> in the last equation.</p>
          <p>Applying the expansion from Equation (9) to Equation (8) gives,</p>
